ects do not notice. The caster may leave after casting, and the subjects continue as if the caster were still present for 1 full round. In such cases, later saving throws for confusion or rage are not made. The spell is entirely verbal.","notes":"","link":"","select_value":"Magic-User: Leomund’s Lamentable Belabourment","class":"Magic-User"},"sending":{"name":"Sending","level":"5","school":"Evocation","range":"Special","duration":"Special","aoe":"One creature","components":"V, S, M","ct":"1 turn","save":"None","save_type":"","description":"Sending\n\nSchool: Evocation\nLevel: 5\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: Special\nCasting Time: 1 turn\nDuration: Special\nSaving Throw: None\nArea of Effect: One creature\nThis spell allows the caster to contact a single creature whose name and appearance are familiar. If the creature is not on the same plane, there is a 5% chance per plane removed that the sending fails to arrive. For example, a subject two planes removed has a 10% failure chance. The magic-user may send one word per caster level; articles such as “a,” “an,” and “the” do not count as words. If successful, the message is understood even by a creature with Intelligence as low as 1, or animal intelligence. The recipient is not obligated to act on the message. Material Component: Two tiny cylinders, each open at one end, connected by a short piece of copper wire.\n\nMagic-User Spells, 6th Level","notes":"","link":"","class":"Magic-User"},"magic user sending":{"name":"Sending","level":"5","school":"Evocation","range":"Special","duration":"Special","aoe":"One creature","components":"V, S, M","ct":"1 turn","save":"None","save_type":"","description":"Sending\n\nSchool: Evocation\nLevel: 5\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: Special\nCasting Time: 1 turn\nDuration: Special\nSaving Throw: None\nArea of Effect: One creature\nThis spell allows the caster to contact a single creature whose name and appearance are familiar. If the creature is not on the same plane, there is a 5% chance per plane removed that the sending fails to arrive. For example, a subject two planes removed has a 10% failure chance. The magic-user may send one word per caster level; articles such as “a,” “an,” and “the” do not count as words. If successful, the message is understood even by a creature with Intelligence as low as 1, or animal intelligence. The recipient is not obligated to act on the message. Material Component: Two tiny cylinders, each open at one end, connected by a short piece of copper wire.\n\nMagic-User Spells, 6th Level","notes":"","link":"","select_value":"Magic-User: Sending","class":"Magic-User"},"chain lightning":{"name":"Chain Lightning","level":"6","school":"Evocation","range":"4” + ½” per level","duration":"Instantaneous","aoe":"Special","components":"V, S, M","ct":"6 segments","save":"Half or negates","save_type":"","description":"Chain Lightning\n\nSchool: Evocation\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: 4” + ½” per level\nCasting Time: 6 segments\nDuration: Instantaneous\nSaving Throw: Half or negates\nArea of Effect: Special\nThis spell begins as a single lightning stroke, ¼” wide, from the caster’s fingertips to a primary target within range. The primary target takes 1d6 damage per caster level, or half damage on a successful saving throw versus spell. After striking the primary target, the lightning arcs to the nearest other object, whether animal, vegetable, or mineral. It continues chaining from object to object, possibly oscillating between two stationary or immobilized targets or forming a pattern among three or more objects. If two or more possible targets are equidistant, the lightning arcs first to metal, then to the target with the most fluid, and otherwise randomly. The spell can strike as many links, including the primary target, as the caster has levels. A 12th-level caster can strike 12 targets: the primary target plus 11 additional links. After the initial strike, each subsequent applicable target may save versus spell. Success means the stroke arcs to the next nearest target and the saving target takes no damage. The bolt continues until it has struck the proper number of objects, until it fades, or until it strikes a grounding target. Direction does not matter, but distance does; a single arc cannot exceed spell range. If an arc would exceed maximum range, the stroke fades. A tree or substantial conductive metal, such as connected iron bars in a large cage, grounds the stroke and stops further arcing. Each target after the first takes one fewer d6 of damage. If the primary target takes 12d6, the next takes 11d6, then 10d6, and so on down to 1d6. A saving throw for half damage applies on each damaging strike. The caster can be struck by an arc from their own spell. Material Components: A bit of fur, an amber, glass, or crystal rod, and one silver pin per caster level.","notes":"","link":"","class":"Magic-User"},"magic user chain lightning":{"name":"Chain Lightning","level":"6","school":"Evocation","range":"4” + ½” per level","duration":"Instantaneous","aoe":"Special","components":"V, S, M","ct":"6 segments","save":"Half or negates","save_type":"","description":"Chain Lightning\n\nSchool: Evocation\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: 4” + ½” per level\nCasting Time: 6 segments\nDuration: Instantaneous\nSaving Throw: Half or negates\nArea of Effect: Special\nThis spell begins as a single lightning stroke, ¼” wide, from the caster’s fingertips to a primary target within range. The primary target takes 1d6 damage per caster level, or half damage on a successful saving throw versus spell. After striking the primary target, the lightning arcs to the nearest other object, whether animal, vegetable, or mineral. It continues chaining from object to object, possibly oscillating between two stationary or immobilized targets or forming a pattern among three or more objects. If two or more possible targets are equidistant, the lightning arcs first to metal, then to the target with the most fluid, and otherwise randomly. The spell can strike as many links, including the primary target, as the caster has levels. A 12th-level caster can strike 12 targets: the primary target plus 11 additional links. After the initial strike, each subsequent applicable target may save versus spell. Success means the stroke arcs to the next nearest target and the saving target takes no damage. The bolt continues until it has struck the proper number of objects, until it fades, or until it strikes a grounding target. Direction does not matter, but distance does; a single arc cannot exceed spell range. If an arc would exceed maximum range, the stroke fades. A tree or substantial conductive metal, such as connected iron bars in a large cage, grounds the stroke and stops further arcing. Each target after the first takes one fewer d6 of damage. If the primary target takes 12d6, the next takes 11d6, then 10d6, and so on down to 1d6. A saving throw for half damage applies on each damaging strike. The caster can be struck by an arc from their own spell. Material Components: A bit of fur, an amber, glass, or crystal rod, and one silver pin per caster level.","notes":"","link":"","select_value":"Magic-User: Chain Lightning","class":"Magic-User"},"contingency":{"name":"Contingency","level":"6","school":"Evocation","range":"0","duration":"1 day per level","aoe":"The magic-user","components":"V, S, M","ct":"1 turn","save":"None","save_type":"","description":"Contingency\n\nSchool: Evocation\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: 0\nCasting Time: 1 turn\nDuration: 1 day per level\nSaving Throw: None\nArea of Effect: The magic-user\nThis spell places another spell upon the magic-user so that the companion spell takes effect when a specified condition occurs. The contingency and companion spell are effectively cast at the same time, within the listed 1-turn casting time. The companion spell must affect the caster’s person, such as feather fall, levitation, fly, statue, feign death, or similar magic. It cannot be higher than one-third the caster’s level, rounded down, to a maximum of 6th-level spell: 4th-level maximum at caster levels 12–14, 5th-level maximum at caster levels 15–17, and 6th-level maximum at caster level 18 or higher. Only one contingency can affect the caster at a time; a second cancels the first. The triggering condition must be clear, though it may be general. For example, airy water might trigger whenever the caster is plunged into water or similar liquid, or feather fall might trigger whenever the caster falls more than 2”. When the prescribed condition occurs, the companion spell activates instantly. Complex, convoluted, or overly complicated conditions may cause the entire spell complex to fail when triggered. Material Components: In addition to the companion spell’s components, 100 gp worth of quicksilver, an elephant ivory statuette of the magic-user, and an eyelash from an ogre mage, ki-rin, or similar spell-using creature. The ivory statuette is not destroyed, but must be carried by the caster for the contingency to function.","notes":"","link":"","class":"Magic-User"},"magic user contingency":{"name":"Contingency","level":"6","school":"Evocation","range":"0","duration":"1 day per level","aoe":"The magic-user","components":"V, S, M","ct":"1 turn","save":"None","save_type":"","description":"Contingency\n\nSchool: Evocation\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: 0\nCasting Time: 1 turn\nDuration: 1 day per level\nSaving Throw: None\nArea of Effect: The magic-user\nThis spell places another spell upon the magic-user so that the companion spell takes effect when a specified condition occurs. The contingency and companion spell are effectively cast at the same time, within the listed 1-turn casting time. The companion spell must affect the caster’s person, such as feather fall, levitation, fly, statue, feign death, or similar magic. It cannot be higher than one-third the caster’s level, rounded down, to a maximum of 6th-level spell: 4th-level maximum at caster levels 12–14, 5th-level maximum at caster levels 15–17, and 6th-level maximum at caster level 18 or higher. Only one contingency can affect the caster at a time; a second cancels the first. The triggering condition must be clear, though it may be general. For example, airy water might trigger whenever the caster is plunged into water or similar liquid, or feather fall might trigger whenever the caster falls more than 2”. When the prescribed condition occurs, the companion spell activates instantly. Complex, convoluted, or overly complicated conditions may cause the entire spell complex to fail when triggered. Material Components: In addition to the companion spell’s components, 100 gp worth of quicksilver, an elephant ivory statuette of the magic-user, and an eyelash from an ogre mage, ki-rin, or similar spell-using creature. The ivory statuette is not destroyed, but must be carried by the caster for the contingency to function.","notes":"","link":"","select_value":"Magic-User: Contingency","class":"Magic-User"},"ensnarement":{"name":"Ensnarement","level":"6","school":"Conjuration/Summoning","range":"1”","duration":"Special","aoe":"Special","components":"V, S, M","ct":"1 turn","save":"Negates","save_type":"","description":"Ensnarement\n\nSchool: Conjuration/Summoning\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: 1”\nCasting Time: 1 turn\nDuration: Special\nSaving Throw: Negates\nArea of Effect: Special\nThis spell lures a powerful creature from another plane to a specially prepared trap, where it is held until it agrees to perform one service in exchange for freedom. The spell creates awareness of a gate-like opening on the creature’s plane. A special saving throw determines whether the creature recognizes the opening as a trap or believes it to be a gate. To save, the creature must roll equal to or below its Intelligence on 3d6, modified by the Intelligence difference between creature and caster. If the creature has higher Intelligence, the difference is subtracted from the roll; if the caster has higher Intelligence, the difference is added. If the save succeeds, the creature ignores the opening and the spell fails. If it fails, the creature steps into the opening and is ensnared. The creature type must be known and stated; if the creature has a specific, proper, or given name, that name must also be used. An ensnared creature is not prevented from harming the caster, so the caster normally uses a magic circle for creatures from the Upper Planes or Astral Plane, a thaumaturgic triangle for creatures from the Ethereal, Elemental, or Concordant Opposition planes, or a pentagram for creatures from the Lower or Infernal Planes. Even so, the creature may break free. A hand-drawn confining design has a 20% base chance of being broken; an inlaid or carved one has a 10% base chance, checked only once. This chance is modified by comparing the caster’s combined Intelligence and experience level to the creature’s Intelligence plus level or Hit Dice. If the caster’s total is higher, the difference is subtracted from the break-free chance; if the creature’s total is higher, the difference is added. Careful preparation can further reduce the chance. A hand-made protection inscribed over time with specially prepared pigments costing 1,000 gp per turn reduces the chance by 1% per turn. An inlaid or inscribed design can be reduced to 0% by inlaying it with suitable metals, minerals, and similar materials, requiring at least one month and adding at least 50,000 gp to the cost. Any break in the lines or blurring of protective glyphs, runes, or sigils spoils the barrier and frees the creature automatically. Even a straw dropped across the circle destroys its power, though the creature inside cannot place anything across the barrier. Once held, the creature may be kept as long as the caster dares. The caster may offer bribes, promises, or threats to exact one service. The DM rates the offer from 0 to 6 and subtracts that value from the creature’s Intelligence. If the creature rolls equal to or below its adjusted Intelligence, it refuses service. New offers may be made after 24 hours, when confinement has reduced its Intelligence by 1. This continues until the creature agrees, breaks free, or the caster releases it by appropriate magic. Once the service is complete, the creature need only inform the caster and is instantly returned from whence it came. Impossible or unreasonable commands are never accepted.","notes":"","link":"","class":"Magic-User"},"magic user ensnarement":{"name":"Ensnarement","level":"6","school":"Conjuration/Summoning","range":"1”","duration":"Special","aoe":"Special","components":"V, S, M","ct":"1 turn","save":"Negates","save_type":"","description":"Ensnarement\n\nSchool: Conjuration/Summoning\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S, M\nRange: 1”\nCasting Time: 1 turn\nDuration: Special\nSaving Throw: Negates\nArea of Effect: Special\nThis spell lures a powerful creature from another plane to a specially prepared trap, where it is held until it agrees to perform one service in exchange for freedom. The spell creates awareness of a gate-like opening on the creature’s plane. A special saving throw determines whether the creature recognizes the opening as a trap or believes it to be a gate. To save, the creature must roll equal to or below its Intelligence on 3d6, modified by the Intelligence difference between creature and caster. If the creature has higher Intelligence, the difference is subtracted from the roll; if the caster has higher Intelligence, the difference is added. If the save succeeds, the creature ignores the opening and the spell fails. If it fails, the creature steps into the opening and is ensnared. The creature type must be known and stated; if the creature has a specific, proper, or given name, that name must also be used. An ensnared creature is not prevented from harming the caster, so the caster normally uses a magic circle for creatures from the Upper Planes or Astral Plane, a thaumaturgic triangle for creatures from the Ethereal, Elemental, or Concordant Opposition planes, or a pentagram for creatures from the Lower or Infernal Planes. Even so, the creature may break free. A hand-drawn confining design has a 20% base chance of being broken; an inlaid or carved one has a 10% base chance, checked only once. This chance is modified by comparing the caster’s combined Intelligence and experience level to the creature’s Intelligence plus level or Hit Dice. If the caster’s total is higher, the difference is subtracted from the break-free chance; if the creature’s total is higher, the difference is added. Careful preparation can further reduce the chance. A hand-made protection inscribed over time with specially prepared pigments costing 1,000 gp per turn reduces the chance by 1% per turn. An inlaid or inscribed design can be reduced to 0% by inlaying it with suitable metals, minerals, and similar materials, requiring at least one month and adding at least 50,000 gp to the cost. Any break in the lines or blurring of protective glyphs, runes, or sigils spoils the barrier and frees the creature automatically. Even a straw dropped across the circle destroys its power, though the creature inside cannot place anything across the barrier. Once held, the creature may be kept as long as the caster dares. The caster may offer bribes, promises, or threats to exact one service. The DM rates the offer from 0 to 6 and subtracts that value from the creature’s Intelligence. If the creature rolls equal to or below its adjusted Intelligence, it refuses service. New offers may be made after 24 hours, when confinement has reduced its Intelligence by 1. This continues until the creature agrees, breaks free, or the caster releases it by appropriate magic. Once the service is complete, the creature need only inform the caster and is instantly returned from whence it came. Impossible or unreasonable commands are never accepted.","notes":"","link":"","select_value":"Magic-User: Ensnarement","class":"Magic-User"},"eyebite":{"name":"Eyebite","level":"6","school":"Enchantment/Charm, Illusion/Phantasm","range":"20 feet","duration":"Special","aoe":"One creature","components":"V, S","ct":"1 segment","save":"Special","save_type":"","description":"Eyebite\n\nSchool: Enchantment/Charm, Illusion/Phantasm\nLevel: 6\nComponents: V, S\nRange: 20 feet\nCasting Time: 1 segment\nDuration: Special\nSaving Throw: Special\nArea of Effect: One creature\nThis spell lets the caster meet the subject’s gaze and speak a single word to activate one chosen effect. Once one of the four effects is used, the spell is dissipated. Charm: The caster charms a person or monster by gaze and word. The subject becomes absolutely loyal and docile toward the caster, even to the point of personal danger. Otherwise, this functions as charm person or charm monster. A successful saving throw versus spell negates it. Fear: The caster causes fear by gaze and word. The subject acts as if affected by a fear spell unless it saves versus spell. Sicken: The caster causes sudden nausea and sickness. The victim functions at half normal ability, including Strength, Intelligence, movement, and similar traits. Creatures without ability scores are unaffected. The victim must rest half of each turn to move at all. A successful saving throw negates the effect. Otherwise, the victim loses 1 Constitution point per day until death at 0 Constitution. The effect is negated by dispel magic or heal. Alter reality, limited wish, and wish also remove it, but cure disease does not. Non-human, non-demi-human, and non-humanoid creatures save at +4 against this effect. Sleep: The caster causes one individual to fall into a comatose slumber unless the subject saves versus spell. Creatures normally subject to the 1st-level sleep spell save at -2. Undead are unaffected. Sleeping creatures must be shaken or otherwise shocked awake.","notes":"","link":"","class":"Magic-User"},"magic use